<TEXT>
here is a condensed transcript of the pentagon 
briefing thursday on recommendations by the defense secretarys 
commission on military base closings participants were deputy 
defense secretary william h taft iv and commission cochairmen 
abraham ribicoff and jack edwards 
ribicoff we believe the results reflect a balanced report to 
eliminate unnecessary installation capacity without restricting the 
flexibility of our national security managers during future 
mobilizations contingencies and changes in the international 
political environment the recommended changes reflect an 
opportunity to improve the nations defense position 
edwards we would like to take this opportunity to thank the 
department and the congress for this opportunity to participate in a 
unique effort which will not only save taxpayers dollars but also 
improve our national defense posture 
during the course of developing our recommendations we used 
improvement in military value of our domestic base structure as the 
preeminent consideration our report presents an opportunity to 
reduce training costs in terms of manpower overhead costs and fuel 
to improve command and control to consolidate training and improve 
economies of scale and to remove unnecessary administrative burdens 
to our defense managers 
add to these improvements an opportunity to eliminate some future 
military construction costs and to save almost 700 million a year 
in base operating costs with a 20year net present value of 56 
billion 
despite these improvements we do not anticipate any substantial 
socioeconomic disruption to the communities that are closely linked 
with bases recommended for closure 
in terms of environmental impact we see little negative impact 
from these recommendations and in many instances improvement for 
the natural surroundings 
ribicoff there are 145 installations affected there are 86 for 
closure five for partial closure 54 bases have been realigned the 
estimation is 693 million saved per year in base operating costs 
and 56 billion to be saved over 20 years on the net present value 
there are about 20 major ones 
edwards i guess generally you would look at the la area fort 
george and the air force base in norton generally you would look 
in illinois at chanute field and fort sheridan generally you would 
probably look at fort devens in massachusetts the washington 
national capital region area which would include meade belvoir and 
holabird you would look at perhaps pease air force base up in new 
hampshire i guess those are the big areas 
ribicoff it goes from page 52 to page 69 in the report and i 
think you will find that to be a very accurate explanation of the 
rationale and what is happening to those bases 
edwards fort dix nj is going into what we call 
semiactive status there will be a group of probably 500 or so 
people there who will maintain it have it available for reserve 
activity have it available for active duty training from time to 
time have it available in the event troops are brought home from 
some part of the world it will be there to support mcguire air 
force base and the naval station at lakehurst 
we broke down all of the military facilities into various 
categories and in our breakdown dix came out at the bottom of the 
list in a category where we had excess capacity basic training 
advanced individual training and these types of things 
we have moved those kinds of activities from dix to various 
facilities in the country some to fort knox some to fort leonard 
wood mo some to fort jackson sc and in the process we moved 
some out of fort bliss in texas so all of it becomes compatible 
what weve tried to do is bring training areas together to the 
extent that we could where we could justify it 
q you mentioned in your opening statement that you didnt expect 
any of these communities to be adversely affected by this i think 
a lot of the communities will find that hard to swallow 
edwards of course they will i said substantial socioeconomic 
impact of course they will have a hard time swallowing it 
there are some areas where the impact is obviously larger than 
others but we have a section in here that deals with ways in 
which communities can help themselves when they feel this kind of 
impact 
the office of economic adjustment in the defense department has a 
great ability to move in and help a community work out its problems 
where possible we have not moved troops across the country but next 
door in the same state or in an adjoining state 
q perhaps you could tell me what sort of thinking went into your 
decision to close the presidio in san francisco 
edwards the presidio sits in the middle of san francisco or 
thereabouts and it cant grow it cant do any more than its 
doing theres no way it can expand its prohibited by laws of 
california and other laws as far as expansion is concerned its in 
a highvalue area and the operations at the presidio can be done by 
and large most anywhere 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

