<DOCNO> AP881230-0041 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
q to what extent does the property value of these bases that 
youve chosen play a role in your decision and how many total 
jobs are we talking about here being lost 
edwards the first thing we looked at was military value without 
a doubt i mean that was our touchstone and if a base had military 
value then we didnt bother it if the base was lacking in military 
value then it became a candidate to look at 
we obviously did not ignore cost savings we used as our 
guideline a sixyear payback as set out in the charter and so if a 
facility did not meet the sixyear payback then its not in our 
list in some instances we looked at estimates as to what we could 
sell the property for but it was not the cornerstone of our 
activity 
q how about the jobs question 
edwards i dont know whether we actually totaled all that 
youll see a column that talks about personnel out and personnel in 
both military and civilian and i think if youll ust run your 
finger down the column to the area youre looking for youll see 
the impact 
q is this the end of it in your mind or can a year from now a 
similar commission come back and recommend a similar number of 
bases i mean a 56 billion savings over a certain number of years 
is rather insignificant when you consider the total defense budget 
ribicoff we think the basic responsibility should be in the 
hands of the secretary of defense there should be an ongoing study 
to see what changes should be made in the bases weve recommended 
that there should be a highlevel small group of people to go over 
this with the secretary of defense but i would hope that there 
wouldnt always be a commission like ours that would be necessary to 
do the whole job over again 
the training is altogether different with the new technology 
were going to have to acquire larger tracts of land many of the 
present bases are limited because they have been surrounded by large 
urban areas and their effectiveness has been destroyed so i think 
the country is going to have to take a good hard look and the 
defense department as to what future training will have to be for 
future wars and the changes that are going to take place 
q can you tell us what the upfront costs of closing and 
realigning these bases are 
edwards well lets see the najavo army depot in arizona just 
to pull one out of there its going to cost 11 million to make 
that move but it will pay back in annual savings 305 million and 
so its going to take us four years to recover that initial cost of 
the move before we start making annual savings but then they are 
annual savings forever 
q as two former members of congress how do you think the 
reaction on the hill will be to this 
edwards i believe the leadership of the armed services 
committees of both the house and the senate favor this exercise 
taking place theres no question that many congressmen and senators 
are going to be upset when they see this list especially if it 
affects their community 
i would anticipate from my own general conversations from 
the time we were appointed to the present that congress will accept 
it 
q there are some lawmakers especially from california who have 
already argued that the the state has been unfairly hit here 
your reaction to that 
edwards a lot of the activity in southern california that is 
reported in here has to do with norton and george they are both 
encroached by air traffic congestion from the la airport they 
cant train adequately because of that problem they both have major 
problems in attracting hightechnology employees because of the 
activity in that area in the civilian sector and we felt that we 
really just had no alternative but to deal with that 
mather air force base calif they are a good distance away 
from their training area they have to fly over 150 nautical miles 
just to get to the area where they train their particular aircraft 
and pilots we have moved them into mountain home idaho where 
there is an electronic training range right there i like to 
think theres a rationale to what weve done 
ribicoff i think they the air force recognize the great 
changes that have taken place in training with the present type of 
equipment and the present time of aircraft and what has happened in 
the urban areas and they realize that changes have to be made and 
california is the fastest growing state in the union when it 
comes to urban encroachment and the elimination of open spaces that 
air forces need 
q what happens if the list is rejected by congress will 
you gentlemen start over 
edwards we are a oneshot unique kind of an organization when 
we hand this report over we are finished 
</TEXT>
