<TEXT>
a chicago native who came to the soviet union 
almost 60 years ago said friday he and his family had won their 
13year fight to leave ending one of the most mixedup soviet 
emigration cases 
abe stolar his wife gita and son michael have been trying to 
emigrate since 1975 at one point in the battle the family got as 
far as the entrance ramp of their plane when soviet officials 
stopped them claiming mrs stolar had access to state secrets in 
her job as a chemist in a geology institute 
theres no feeling yet its just a big mess thinking of all 
the things we have to do the 77yearold stolar a jew said in 
an interview with the associated press 
they drag it out so long its been 13 years the main thing 
now is to try to be calm and not to forget anything which is hard 
stolar and his family plan to go to israel but he said they did 
not know yet when they will leave after settling in israel he 
said the family will go to the united states to visit friends 
resolution of the case was another in a series of soviet moves 
under mikhail s gorbachev to improve the countrys human rights 
record many jews who were refused permission for years have 
emigrated in the past year and a half 
stolar came to the soviet union as a teenager in 1931 with his 
parents who were russian emigres and ardent communists his father 
died in josef stalins purges stolar was disenchanted with the 
country to which he came to help build the first communist power 
but he was stuck 
stolar was called up to fight in the red army during world war 
ii where a nazi grenade cost him the sight in his left eye he 
later served as a translator and announcer for radio moscow 
stolar holds us citizenship as does his son by virtue of 
stolars birth and residence in the united states 
the family was stripped of its soviet citizenship in 1975 that 
was when they were stopped at the entrance ramp of their plane for 
10 years the soviets refused to let mrs stolar leave their 
belongings have remained in a warehouse in israel ever since 
in the mid1980s the family received final permission to leave 
but stolar had a new problem his sons new wife julia is a soviet 
citizen and her mother refused to sign a financial waiver allowing 
her to go the family refused to leave without julia and mother and 
daughter have not been on speaking terms for many years 
the stolar case has been high on the list of ussoviet human 
rights cases for years officials reported several times that it was 
solved but new problems cropped up 
i have news now an excited stolar said starting his 
telephone conversation 
julia who has a 2yearold daughter and an 8monthold son 
said in an interview that the soviet foreign ministry told us 
embassy officials about five days ago that her mother finally had 
signed a release allowing her to go 
she said she called the soviet visa and registration office 
ovir on friday and that deputy director ilya karakulkov had 
confirmed that officials received the signed waiver she said she 
expects to receive official notification in the next several days 
im sure there was pressure on my mother julia said they 
called her into ovir several times 
she said she did not know why her mother finally signed the 
release and in no circumstances would call her to find out 
she said many jews remain behind in hopeless situations 
because their relatives refuse to sign waivers permitting them to 
emigrate 
michael 29 said he had no special feelings he said he 
worried about friends who want to emigrate but dont have the us 
government on their side like his family did 
sen paul simon dill who met with stolar credited gorbachev 
for the decision to allow stolar to return to the united states 
ive worked on hundreds of soviet emigration cases over the 
years and this has been the toughest and the most frustrating 
simon said from his home in makanda ill 
i dont believe it would have been settled without president 
gorbachevs direct involvement its also a hopeful sign about 
gorbachevs struggle with his own bureaucracy abe stolar loves his 
hometown and were going to give him a grand tour when he comes 
back 
simon said the chicago hilton has agreed to put stolar and his 
family up free of charge when he returns stolar had told simon a 
boyhood dream was to stay a night and live like a king in the 
old steven hotel which is now the hilton 
stolar told simon were trying to make plans we just want to 
find a small quiet town someplace green no hurlyburly i hope i 
can find work 
