<TEXT>
a judge friday blocked the 
government from proceeding with plans to place 9000 rural blacks 
under the jurisdiction of a tribal homeland against their wishes 
the ruling came hours after president pw botha issued a 
proclamation that the braklaagte community would become part of the 
nominally independent homeland of bophuthatswana on saturday 
pretoria supreme court justice tt spoelstra blocked immediate 
implementation of the proclamation and gave the government until 
march 7 to show why its plan shouldnt be invalidated 
the leader of the braklaagte community chief pupsey sebogodi 
contended in court papers that his people faced hardship and 
discrimination if they were incorporated into bophuthatswana they 
live in a farming area about 100 miles west of pretoria 
the community has voiced opposition in the past to the 
bophuthatswana government and has sought to retain south african 
citizenship because of advantages in seeking employment residents 
feared that if they were incorporated into bophuthatswana they 
would be victimized unless they became citizens of the homeland 
the intended incorporation was part of the governments 
longstanding and controversial policy of locating various black 
ethnic groups in selfgoverning or nominally independent homelands 
to reduce the proportion of blacks to whites in the rest of south 
africa 
this policy suffered major defeats in court twice in 1988 
the countrys highest court the appeal court ruled in april 
that botha acted without authority when he incorporated the 
120000member community of moutse into the adjoining 
semiautonomous homeland of kwandebele northeast of pretoria 
the incorporation provoked widespread violence in moutse where 
most residents do not belong to the ndebele tribe that predominates 
in kwandebele 
in august the orange free state provincial supreme court 
rejected a government plan to place botshabelo a vast black 
shantytown under the jurisdiction of the qwaqwa an impoverished 
homeland 180 miles away 
a threejudge panel said the merger would not promote the 
political development of botshabelos estimated 500000 residents 
zach de beer leader of the antiapartheid progressive federal 
party criticized the attempt to excise braklaagte from south africa 
after the abject failure of the homelands policy during many 
years it is almost incredible that as 1989 opens the government 
should yet again be forcing south africans against their will to 
become inhabitants of one of these places he said 
bophuthatswana is made up of seven separate pieces of territory 
in northcentral south africa it has an estimated 17 million 
residents and covers 18000 square miles 
under apartheid the 26 million blacks in south africa have no 
vote in national affairs the 5 million whites control the economy 
and maintain separate districts schools and health services 
