<TEXT>
prime minister noboru takeshita appointed his second 
justice minister of the week friday as his scandalbuffeted 
government lurched toward the end of what commentators are calling a 
gloomy year in japanese politics 
takeshita had to reach outside the world of politics to name a 
new justice minister picking masami takatsuji 78 a former supreme 
court justice with experience in drafting legislation as a 
bureaucrat in the 1960s and 1970s 
on tuesday the prime minister appointed takashi hasegawa a 
76yearold member of parliament to the justice portfolio 
but hasegawa lasted only 60 hours said to be a postwar record 
for short cabinet tenure as it became known he had received 
donations for years from recruit co which the justice ministry is 
investigating on suspicion of bribery 
at the root of japans political gloom is the scandal involving 
the recruit conglomerate whose founder sold unlisted shares of a 
subsidiary at bargain prices to politicians their aides and 
business leaders the share prices more than doubled when they were 
publicly listed in 1986 and the holders made fat taxfree profits 
when they sold 
the recruit scandal has been dubbed the top story of the year by 
japanese media rivaled only by the similarly downbeat story of the 
illness of emperor hirohito 87 who has been bedridden with 
intestinal hemorrhaging since sept 19 
the year 1988 was an indescribably gloomy one for japanese 
politics and one that calls for much soulsearching commentator 
minoru tada wrote in fridays japan times he said japans 
leadership is deeply tainted by money power 
an editorial friday in the asahi shimbun another newspaper said 
the justconcluded session of parliament showed japanese politics 
at its ugliest and most corrupt 
as hasegawa gave up the justice portfolio friday some opposition 
leaders and analysts said takeshita should resign his entire 
government and call elections 
takeshita who had appointed hasegawa tuesday along with a new 
cabinet in a drive to restore public confidence in government did 
not immediately comment on the major setback 
instead the outgoing and incoming justice ministers spoke to 
reporters hasegawa apologized and said he hadnt known until 
wednesday that recruit had been giving money to his political 
support organization since 1976 
however as minister in charge of clearing up the recruit 
problem in the takeshita administration which is trying to heighten 
trust in government it is regrettable that i received donations 
from recruit he said 
the scandal now has brought the resignations of 18 public figures 
including two cabinet members since it hit the front pages last 
summer business leaders top bureaucrats and news media executives 
are among the casualties 
after hasegawas donations from recruit became known three other 
members of the cabinet also said the company had donated to them 
making it apparent that takeshita would have to go outside his 
liberal democratic party to find a justice minister untainted by 
recruit money 
takatsuji who served on the supreme court from 1973 to 1980 
said he had no connection at all to the recruit firm 
i dont really have anything to say about recruit takatsuji 
said my attitude toward it is no different from that of the 
people in general 
public approval of takeshitas government has slumped badly since 
he became prime minister in november 1987 a mainichi shimbun 
newspaper poll in december showed his approval had dropped from 30 
percent to 18 percent and a kyodo news service poll showed his 
approval rating down to 359 percent from 548 percent three months 
earlier 
takeshita himself has a recruit link since an aide and a relative 
profited from shares in the recruitcosmos subsidiary but he says 
he was not personally involved 
his popularity also has suffered from the railroading of a 
controversial tax reform through the diet or parliament 
some analysts expect takeshita will face further setbacks if 
there are arrests in the recruit affair and as the opposition uses 
the scandal to try to block passage of the budget in the diet 
since takeshita had advocated the importance of public 
consensus he and his administration should resign as public 
support goes lower said masayuki fukuoka a political science 
professor at komazawa university in tokyo 
despite the polls many analysts think the japanese are inured to 
shady practices under the governing conservatives who have held 
power for all the postwar years except for 10 months in 194748 
the japanese take it for granted said garrett n scalera 
president of the tokyo institute of policy studies i think they 
may be rather blase about this 
the pervasiveness of shady money was shown in a report issued 
friday by the national tax agency which estimated that japanese 
firms had spent 456 million in 1987 on such shady expenses as 
illegal political donations and backdoor rebates to other firms 
the figure was a record up 24 percent from the previous high in 
1984 the agency said 
