<DOCNO> AP881230-0116 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
air terrorism has spawned a grisly arms race 
between the security establishment and the everincreasing 
sophistication of the terrorist arsenal 
as bombdetection machinery has grown more refined explosives 
have become easier to conceal as one security gap closes 
terrorists find another 
because of lack of personnel and the expense of operating xray 
equipment we are always at least two steps behind the 
terrorists brian orrell of the british flight engineers union 
said friday eight days after a bomb blew up pan am flight 103 over 
scotland killing all 259 people aboard and leaving 11 on the ground 
missing and presumed dead 
but other experts say the quest for terroristproof air travel 
has reached an outer limit beyond which it will become prohibitively 
expensive or make flying unbearably uncomfortable 
when air terrorism became a problem in the late 1960s 
authorities responded by transforming airports into fortresses 
it now is routine for all passengers to go through metal 
detectors while their hand luggage is xrayed airlines especially 
at risk such as israels el al search all luggage by hand at 
belfast airports the irish terrorist threat makes it necessary to 
frisk not just the passengers but everyone else coming into the 
terminal 
airlines insist that each piece of luggage match its passenger 
assuming that no bomber would travel aboard the targeted plane so 
terrorists have resorted to duping unwitting passengers into 
carrying explosives onto planes passengers are regularly warned to 
accept no baggage they havent packed themselves 
the search for suspicious objects has become much harder with the 
advent of plastic explosives that give off virtually no detectable 
odor they are malleable enough to be shaped into a souvenir or 
rolled waferthin to fit inside a suitcase lining detonators now 
are small enough to fit into a suitcase lock 
moreover the age of the metalfree handgun is looming according 
to david kyd spokesman for the international air transport 
association in geneva such a gun has been developed in austria and 
will be extremely hard to detect on xray screens 
the sophistication and miniaturization of explosives has become 
quite worrisome kyd said in an interview 
according to david learmount of the respected journal flight 
international its an arms race 
bombs can be connected to barometric detonators that respond to 
altitude changes airports have hit back by putting baggage through 
simulated pressure to set off such bombs in safety 
the terrorists in turn have come up with a doubledevice the 
pressure detonator goes off safely but it activates a second timer 
that will detonate the bomb in the air 
the times of london said friday that this method was believed to 
have been used on flight 103 
kyd is optimistic that within two years a highly advanced 
explosives detector will become operational 
now being tested in us laboratories the machine bombards 
objects with thermoneutron rays that detect telltale nitrogen 
vapors but to cover the vast amount of baggage moving through large 
airports it will have to be small mobile and able to distinguish 
explosives vapors from those given off by aviation fuel said kyd 
he said the biggest security hole now lies not in the terminals 
where passengers arrive to catch flights but on the tarmac where the 
planes are parked 
security he said is difficult to impose on the hundreds of 
airport workers swarming about the tarmac many of the menial jobs 
are held by lowpaid immigrants who are vulnerable to bribery and 
whose background is unverifiable in a security screening 
we can put all the screens in place to check passengers and 
luggage but theres still the problem of direct access to aircraft 
by people who are there to clean planes fuel them and put food 
aboard he said 
the weapons used in the hijacking of a kuwaiti airliner by 
iranian extremists this year were probably smuggled aboard in 
catering trolleys in bangkok kyd said 
a huge amount can still be done for security but the fact that 
its possible doesnt mean its feasible learmount said in an 
interview 
el al is unique he said because israel as a nation operates 
in some respects under siege under military conditions and all its 
citizens accept that so its airline has to act in many respects 
like a military operation 
el al passengers have to check in three hours before takeoff 
their baggage is handsearched and the slightest irregularity in a 
travel document can mean a polite but lengthy interrogation about 
the passengers origins work family friends and purpose of travel 
if another airline used such tactics on passengers learmount 
said i suspect they wouldnt keep on flying with you for very 
long 
el al has never had an aircraft bombed but an el al boeing 707 
was hijacked over italian airspace by three armed members of the 
popular front for the liberation of palestine on july 23 1968 all 
passengers and crew were freed over several days after the plane 
landed in algeria 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

