<TEXT>
the farmers home administration said friday it 
will begin next week a 200 million loan guarantee program for rural 
businesses that suffered from the 1988 drought and other weather 
disasters 
acting fmha administrator la verne ausman said the program was 
authorized by congress in the 1988 disaster assistance act new 
regulations carrying out the program will be put into effect on jan 
3 although they will have a 60day period for public comment 
ausman said the agency can make any changes that may be 
necessary after the 60day comment period is over meanwhile he 
said many rural businesses are in need of assistance the maximum 
loan amount is 500000 
under the program fmha can guarantee up to 90 percent of a loan 
to help alleviate financial distress caused directly or 
indirectly by drought hail excessive moisture or related 
conditions that occurred in 1988 he said 
the program will be similar in most respects to the existing fmha 
business and industrial or bampi guaranteed loans the loans will be 
made by regular commercial lenders at negotiated interest rates 
with fmha guarantees providing protection against loss should the 
loans fail 
ausman said the main difference is that the drought and disaster 
program will guarantee only the principal while the bampi program 
guarantees both principal and interest 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

