<TEXT>
the government resigned friday in 
reaction to mounting criticism of its handling of an economic 
crisis the first to do so since the communists took power after 
world war ii 
the move a sign of the liberalization creeping into yugoslavias 
oneparty system represented a further break with the legacy of 
president josip broz tito founder of communist yugoslavia and its 
undisputed leader until his death in 1980 
premier branko mikulic told parliament he and the entire 
31member cabinet stepped down because legislators refused wednesday 
to pass an economic law needed to ensure continued support from the 
international monetary fund 
mikulic a 60yearold economist and tito ally who took office in 
may 1986 was seen as a hardliner in the ruling communist party his 
resignation indicated that reformoriented forces eager to adopt 
westernstyle changes are gaining the upper hand in a protracted 
political struggle 
few yugoslavs however expected mikulics resignation to bring 
any immediate solutions to an economic crisis that has reduced 
living standards by 50 percent since 1980 
foreign debt stands at 21 billion unemployment at 15 percent 
and inflation at around 250 percent three times what it was when 
mikulic took office 
in a speech to parliament broadcast on live national television 
mikulic firmly rejected responsibility for the countrys economic 
and social woes effectively blaming the system bequeathed by tito 
he said difficulties created in past decades could not be solved in 
the 2 years he has spent in office 
mikulic will stay in office as a caretaker premier until the 
nineman federal presidency names a new government in january 
the complex federal system bequeathed by tito stipulates that all 
federal decisions must be unanimously agreed on by yugoslavias six 
constituent republics and two autonomous provinces 
in practice this has meant that federal decisions are watered 
down to ineffectual compromises that each region interprets as it 
wants 
referring to yugoslavias maze of federal republican and local 
bureaucracies and laws mikulic told parliament that decisions about 
the economy are made in 7000 to 8000 different places suggesting 
it was unfair to blame the government 
falling living standards have provoked more than 1000 strikes 
this year in a country once hailed as a workermanaged state 
discontent also has eaten at the prestige of the communist party 
whose membership has fallen steadily 
two belgrade residents who asked not to be named said they 
expected little to change after the first fall of a communist 
government in yugoslavia 
did they fall indeed a travel agent asked upon being told 
the news so who is going to congratulate us for the new year 
she quipped 
a housewife shopping before the threeday new year holiday 
lamented the difficulty of making ends meet each month 
so what do you expect will happen now she said they are 
all of a kind they cannot do anything or do not want to except 
build seaside villas at the expense of the workers 
she was referring to a scandal in mikulics native republic of 
bosniahercegovina where hundreds of party officials have been 
accused of securing illegal loans to build themselves homes in the 
adriatic resort of neum 
mikulic survived an attempted vote of confidence in may when 
parliamentary deputies from the liberal northern republic of 
slovenia and from croatia failed to gain support from four other 
republics for mikulics ouster 
but criticism had mounted in recent weeks government minister 
oskar kovac who oversaw yugoslavias negotiations with its debtors 
resigned dec 5 citing unidentified pressures that hindered 
marketoriented reform 
ironically parliament on thursday passed a package of economic 
reform laws that should allow mixed ownership and greater foreign 
investment measures economists have long prescribed for 
yugoslavias economic ills 
increasing poverty has exacerbated traditional ethnic conflicts 
among the more than 30 ethnic groups who make up yugoslavias 23 
million citizens 
but parliament on wednesday defied mikulics warnings about the 
need to live up to its obligations to the international monetary 
fund refusing to pass a law curbing public spending 
such austerity measures are a condition of imf aid to 
inflationridden countries such as yugoslavia mikulic said the imf 
had demanded the law as a condition for granting the belgrade 
government a oneyear 416 million standby credit in june 
some 260 million of that credit has been used to date according 
to official estimates the loan also encouraged western creditors to 
reschedule payments on yugoslavias mounting foreign debt 
