<TEXT>
thomas c blaisdell jr recognized as 
one of the key designers of the marshall plan that restored a 
devastated europe after world war ii has died at the age of 93 
blaisdell who died tuesday was a distinguished professor of 
political science at the university of californiaberkeley who 
continued teaching long after assuming emeritus status in 1963 
a native of pittsburgh blaisdell joined the administration of 
president franklin d roosevelt in 1933 where he worked on the 
consumers council and in the agricultural adjustment administration 
over the next two decades he held a number of federal positions 
working first on helping the nation recover from the depression and 
then on european postwar reconstruction 
blaisdell was assistant secretary of commerce during the 
administration of president harry s truman and it was from hat 
office that he became the man many colleagues described as the 
principal designer of the marshall plan 
blaisdell earned a bachelors degree at pennsylvania state 
college in 1916 he did postgraduate work at columbia university 
earning a masters degree in social history in 1922 and a doctorate 
in 1932 he taught at columbia from 1925 to 1932 
he joined the berkeley faculty in 1951 a frequent author 
perhaps his bestknown work was published in 1976 the book the 
american presidency in political cartoons was written with 
berkeley art history professor peter selz 
blaisdell is survived by a son thomas a brother william two 
grandchildren and two greatgrandchildren 
</TEXT>
