<TEXT>
an influential west german admiral 
wrote in a magazine article that west germany should stop acting as 
washingtons model boy support abolishment of shortrange 
nuclear arms and seek peace with moscow 
in an article written for this weeks edition of stern weekly 
magazine adm elmar schmaeling promoted policies he said would lead 
to withdrawal of foreign troops from west germany and other european 
countries 
about 400000 foreign troops including 250000 from the united 
states are stationed on west german territory a spate of crashes 
of nato warplanes this year has heightened public controversy over 
the troops 
schmaeling serves as chief of the west german armed forces 
office for studies and exercises a think tank 
he has made comments in the past similar to those in the stern 
article 
he wrote in stern that it was time to reexamine the 
foundations of our postwar policies because of changes in the 
soviet bloc 
he argued that the united states believes eventual conflict with 
the soviet union is inevitable in contrast he wrote west germans 
want to overcome confrontation with the warsaw pact 
the goal is an international system of common security in 
europe he wrote 
schmaeling said that for too long we have been playing the role 
of model boy to appear reliable friendly and grateful friends 
of the united states 
the united states owns the shortrange or tactical nuclear 
weapons stationed in west germany the soviet union keeps such 
weapons in east germany and czechoslovakia 
nuclear weapons should be allowed to be stationed only on the 
territory of the country that also has them at their disposal 
schmaeling wrote 
he called for pursuit of disarmament policies that would lead to 
ending the unnatural situation of foreign troops on ones own 
territory 
a speededup process of mutual disarmament and the dismantling 
also of conventional invasion weapons must lead to military 
structures that are purely defensive in all countries 
when this is mutually done military alliances with 
integrated forces can be dissolved he wrote 
defense minister rupert scholz and other west german officials 
say foreign troops and shortrange nuclear weapons are needed here 
to offset what they view as a soviet threat 
