<TEXT>
part of an artillery shell containing 
conventional explosives and depleted uranium was accidentally 
shipped to the sandia national laboratories a newspaper reported 
friday 
the test shell sat at the lab for four days in august 1987 before 
it was discovered said the san jose mercury news 
depleted uranium is incapable of causing a nuclear explosion and 
only slightly radioactive but it is poisonous when inhaled 
officials at sandias main facility in albuquerque nm said 
the risk of a conventional explosion was very low 
it didnt pose any danger said nigel hey a sandia spokesman 
in albuquerque on friday the thing is we just didnt follow the 
rules 
the shell was shipped to the lab as unclassified freight from the 
tonopah test range in nevada where a clerk mixed it up with another 
shipment the shell was to have remained there for a future 
shipment where it would have been properly labeled 
the wooden crate carrying the device should have been marked as 
classified package containing explosive and radioactive material 
hey said it was supposed to be shipped to a secret weapons testing 
site at the lawrence livermore national laboratory 
instead it was flown to the alameda naval air station by a 
government contractor and carried to the sandia lab by a department 
of energy truck as a routine delivery the shell was placed under 
armed guard after its discovery 
it caused a lot of concern and it was taken as an example of 
how things can go wrong hey said test range officials have since 
revised shipping rules 
