colombia for the first time friday 
suspended payment on its 165billion foreign debt for three 
months when the government is to obtain a new loan to meet the 
payments 
treasury minister luis fernando alarcon who announced the 
decision said the countrys creditors agreed to the suspension 
colombia was the only latin american country up to now that had 
not restructured its debt or suspended its payments 
the minister said colombia will receive in april an international 
loan of 17 billion that will ensure it will have the funds needed 
to pay interest and principal on the foreign debt until 1990 
the 90day moratorium means colombia will not pay 300 million 
which can be used for economic development programs he told a news 
conference 
the 300 million will be paid after colombia receives the 
additional loan he said 
colombia had asked for a 185 billion loan in negotiations with 
international bankers to pay its foreign debt 
political leaders and economic analysts had recommended that 
president virgilio barcos government renegotiate the foreign debt 
under more favorable terms in recent years 40 percent of 
colombias income from exports has been spent to service the debt 
congress last week approved a law making it easier for the 
government to renegotiate the debt with its creditors saying it was 
impossible to continue paying the debt under the current schedule 
