<DOCNO> AP881230-0183 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
isamu noguchi the renowned american sculptor 
whose work graces museums gardens and parks around the world died 
friday after a brief illness he was 84 
noguchi whose work blended the esthetics of east and west was 
best known for monumental public sculpture but also designed 
furniture and lamps stage sets gardens fountains playgrounds and 
worked in several artistic media 
he received the national medal of arts from president reagan at 
the white house in june 1987 
he was one of the most important artists of the 20th century 
said jennifer russell associate director of the whitney museum of 
american art his career had an extraordinary range 
among his works are the gleaming steel dodge memorial fountain in 
detroit a 28foot red cube that stands on one of its corners in 
front of a lower manhattan bank and the sunken garden at new yorks 
chase manhattan plaza he also designed the unesco garden in paris 
the billy rose sculpture garden in jerusalem and two bridges for 
hiroshimas peace park 
noguchi worked in many materials including wood bronze and 
galvanized steel but his major sculptures are made of stone 
basalt granite and marble 
he is represented in the permanent collections of such major 
american museums as the metropolitan whitney and modern in new 
york the art institute of chicago the detroit art institute 
seattle art museum and walker arts center in minneapolis 
america has lost its greatest living sculptor said allen 
wardwell director of the isamu noguchi garden museum in queens 
of course he was much more than a sculptor he was a designer of 
spaces stage sets gardens fountains and the decorative arts he 
was a great thinker and visionary 
art was it he wrote a lot but it was about art wardwell 
said 
he was very much an innovator and not a follower said ms 
russell 
noguchi once said he was suspicious of the whole business of 
style again it is a form of inhibition 
wardwell said noguchi died at new york university medical center 
at 2 am friday of heart failure 
at the time of his death he had just returned from italy and was 
working on several large marble sculptures among other projects 
including the bayfront park in miami a memorial to the challenger 
astronauts he had just been commissioned to do a major park for the 
city of sapporo japan 
noguchi lived in new york but spent much time in japan including 
his formative years and he employed numerous artisans at a large 
workshop in takamatsu on the japanese island of shikoku 
the son of a japanese poet and an american writer he was born in 
los angeles on nov 17 1904 but two years later his family took 
him to tokyo he returned alone to the united states in 1918 and 
went to school in indiana 
noguchi entered columbia university as a premedical student in 
1922 but dropped out in favor of sculpture studies at the leonardo 
da vinci art school now defunct 
he moved to paris in 1928 and became a studio assistant for 
constantin brancusi for six months during that time his earliest 
works were made noguchi returned to new york in 1929 and had his 
first oneman show at the eugene schoen gallery 
he survived on the sales of a few bronze head portraits and on 
grants including a guggenheim fellowship in 1927 which enabled him 
to travel to japan and china where he studied drawing inkbrush 
painting and pottery 
one of his first competitive successes was a 1938 commission for 
the 10ton stainlesssteel relief above the entrance to the 
associated press building at rockefeller center the piece one of 
his few representational pieces depicts five journalists at work 
his sculptures were often smoothsurfaced vaguely biological 
forms that remind some scholars of the surrealistic paintings of 
joan miro and of primitive japanese haniwa figures in later 
years his work became more geometric while retaining organic 
imagery 
the naturalistic style was once described in the new york times 
as a restrained vocabulary of organic forms ranging from playful 
biomorphs and abstract figures to subtle mounds polished rings and 
massive boulders 
he said he was fascinated by abandoned stones that allow me 
to enter into their lifes purpose 
his works are found outside the united states at tokyos museum 
of modern art the art gallery of ontario in toronto the 
rijksmuseum krollermuller in otterlo the netherlands the ulster 
museum in belfast northern ireland and the bayerische vereinsbank 
in munich west germany 
noguchi had an active social life but lived modestly in a small 
apartment he was married briefly to the japanese actress yoshiko 
yamaguchi but they were separated by immigration difficulties and 
later divorced they had no children he is survived by a sister 
ailes spinden of santa fe nm 
there will be a memorial service at the noguchi garden museum 
feb 7 but the funeral and burial services will be private 
wardwell said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

