<TEXT>
the governments chief economic forecasting gauge edged down 02 
percent in november continuing a seesaw pattern that analysts said 
portends a slowdown but no recession in 1989 
the commerce departments report friday on its index of leading 
economic indicators was viewed as good news by some experts who 
said it should ease fears that the economy was growing at a pace 
that threatened new inflation 
the 02 percent november decline was the fourth drop in the past 
seven months since may the index has alternated between gains and 
declines showing very little forward momentum and suggesting 
overall economic growth will slow significantly in 1989 
in another signal of slower growth the government reported 
friday that sales of new homes fell by 8 percent in november the 
biggest decline in 18 months analysts blamed the setback on rising 
mortgage rates likely to further dampen sales in 1989 
the last government numbers of 1988 had little or no influence 
over the financial markets which closed out the final trading day 
of the year with mixed results in light trading 
bond prices rose slightly the dollar weakened marginally against 
key currencies and the dow jones industrial average fell 1411 
points to close at 216857 though advancing issues slightly 
outnumbered declines on the new york stock exchange 
the reagan administration said the setback in the leading index 
was nothing to become alarmed over showing only that the economy 
was slowing a bit the traditional signal for a recession in the 
past has been at least three consecutive monthly declines in the 
index 
private analysts agreed forecasting that overall economic 
growth as measured by the gross national product will probably dip 
to around 25 percent in 1989 that would be down from an expected 
growth rate of 39 percent in 1988 the economys best performance 
in four years 
